2.1 Installing Node.js

Check Node version: open a terminal or Command Prompt and run:

node --version

If you see a version number like v18.17.0 or higher, Node is already installed. If you get “command not found” or the version is below 18, install Node.

Install using Node Version Manager (recommended):

On macOS or Linux, install nvm by running:

curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.4/install.sh | bash
# Then restart your terminal and install Node 18 LTS
nvm install 18
nvm use 18

On Windows, download the Node.js LTS installer from nodejs.org
 and run it. Make sure to tick “Automatically install the necessary tools”.

2.2 Installing the Worker project

Clone or download the repository that contains the Worker code. If you cloned using Git:

git clone https://github.com/your-org/vinti4-worker.git
cd vinti4-worker

If you don’t have Git, download the ZIP file from your project hosting platform, extract it, and open the extracted folder in a terminal.

Install dependencies using npm:

npm install

This command reads the package.json file and installs required packages (e.g., Jest for testing, Cloudflare Wrangler, etc.).

Install Cloudflare Wrangler (optional): The wrangler CLI allows you to run Workers locally and deploy to Cloudflare. Install it globally:

npm install -g wrangler

Verify installation with:

wrangler --version

Set up environment variables: Create a file named .env in the project root with your POS credentials and any other secrets. For example:

POS_ID=20314869
POS_AUTH_CODE=ttqRdOzmGvCSpuag
CALLBACK_URL=https://your-worker-domain.com/callback
PORTAL_ID=your-portal-id
PORTAL_PASSWORD=your-portal-password

Never commit this file to version control. It should be used only in development.

(Optional) Configure Wrangler: run wrangler login and follow the instructions to authenticate with Cloudflare. This step is only needed if you plan to deploy the Worker to Cloudflare or use wrangler dev to bind D1 databases.
3. Running the Unit Tests

Unit tests verify your fingerprint and helper functions without making network requests. They run quickly and catch most errors early.

Execute all tests:

npm test

This command uses Jest (or the testing framework specified in package.json) to run all test files in the test directory. The provided test suite should include tests for:

sha512Base64 – verifying the raw SHA‑512 + Base64 behaviour.
buildSendFingerprint – checking that the send fingerprint matches known examples from the specification.
buildResponseFingerprint – checking the success and error fingerprints against known values.

If a test fails, read the failure message. Usually it will show the expected output and the actual output. Make sure you’ve implemented the functions exactly as specified.

Troubleshooting:
If sha512Base64 fails, verify that you’re using the raw digest, not the hex string. The length of a SHA‑512 digest should be 64 bytes (128 hex characters), but Base64 output should be 88 characters.
If the send fingerprint test fails, ensure you multiply the amount by 1000 and remove whitespace. Check the concatenation order.
If the response fingerprint test fails, double‑check the order of fields, strip leading zeros from CP and TID, and trim whitespace.
4. Running the Worker Locally

You can simulate the Worker on your own machine using either the Node.js entry point (if provided) or Cloudflare Wrangler. The steps below use Wrangler.

Start the Worker in development mode:

wrangler dev

By default, this serves the Worker on http://localhost:8787. The console output will show the port; if it differs, use that.

Observe logs: Wrangler prints console logs from your Worker. When sending requests, watch this terminal for fingerprint comparison results, error messages and session updates.
5. Testing the /create-payment endpoint
5.1 Sending a payment request

Prepare a sample order. You’ll need an order ID, amount (integer CVE), and customer data. For example:

{
  "orderId": "12345",
  "amount": 5000,
  "customer": {
    "email": "alice@example.com",
    "phone": "+238 9988776",
    "billingAddress1": "Avenida Cidade",
    "billingCity": "Praia",
    "billingCountryAlpha2": "CV",
    "billingPostcode": "0000"
  },
  "locale": "pt"
}

Use Postman or curl to POST to /create-payment:

With Postman:

Create a new POST request to http://localhost:8787/create-payment.
Select Body > raw and choose JSON. Paste the JSON above.
Send the request. You should see a response containing an HTML form. In most cases, the Worker will return a 200 with an HTML body that auto‑submits. To view it, click Preview in Postman.

With curl:

curl -X POST http://localhost:8787/create-payment \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"orderId":"12345","amount":5000,"customer":{"email":"alice@example.com","phone":"+238 9988776","billingAddress1":"Avenida Cidade","billingCity":"Praia","billingCountryAlpha2":"CV","billingPostcode":"0000"},"locale":"pt"}'

The response will be the auto‑submit HTML. Save it to a file if you wish to inspect the hidden fields.

Check the logs: In the terminal where wrangler dev is running, you should see logs indicating the generated fingerprint and the URL used for the SISP POST. If the fingerprint looks strange (for example, it is null or very short), there may be a bug in the algorithm.
5.2 Common issues
Missing fields: If the response from /create-payment contains an error about missing fields, ensure your request body includes orderId, amount and the required customer details. Use integer CVE for amount, not a string or decimal.
Fingerprint mismatch: If you later see a mismatch at the callback stage, confirm that the Worker uses the same values sent to SISP when computing the fingerprint. Logging the values helps you diagnose this.
6. Testing the /callback endpoint

SISP will normally call your /callback endpoint after the customer completes the payment. To test this locally, simulate SISP’s POST using your own data.

6.1 Simulating a success callback

Generate a valid callback payload: Use the same values you provided in /create-payment and compute the response fingerprint using your buildResponseFingerprint function. For example:

node scripts/build-callback.js --autCode ttqRdOzmGvCSpuag --messageType 8 --cp 0001 --tid 0012 --ref R20240510153000 --sess R20240510153000 --amount 5000 --msgId TESTMSGID --pan "************1234" --resp C --timestamp "2024-05-10 15:35:00" --reference "" --entity "" --receipt "REC123" --additional "" --reloadCode "000000000000"

The script should output a JSON or URL‑encoded body and the fingerprint. If you don’t have such a script, you can write one or manually assemble the payload.

Send the POST:

curl -X POST http://localhost:8787/callback \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "messageType=8&merchantRespCP=0001&merchantRespTid=0012&merchantRespMerchantRef=R20240510153000&merchantRespMerchantSession=R20240510153000&merchantRespPurchaseAmount=5000&merchantRespMessageID=TESTMSGID&merchantRespPan=************1234&merchantResp=C&merchantRespTimeStamp=2024-05-10%2015:35:00&merchantRespReferenceNumber=&merchantRespEntityCode=&merchantRespClientReceipt=REC123&merchantRespAdditionalErrorMessage=&merchantRespReloadCode=000000000000&resultFingerPrint=YOUR_COMPUTED_FINGERPRINT&resultFingerPrintVersion=1"
Observe logs: The Worker should log whether the fingerprint matched and whether the amount matched. If both match, it should mark the session as successful and (optionally) send a notification to WooCommerce asynchronously. If anything doesn’t match, it should log the mismatch and mark the session as failed.
6.2 Simulating an error callback
Change merchantResp to D and messageType to 10 or 6 and compute a new fingerprint. Send this POST to /callback.
Verify that the Worker logs the error and does not update the order or session to success. The session should be marked as failed or denied.
6.3 Caveats
Order lookup: The Worker uses merchantRespMerchantRef to find the session and associated WooCommerce order, not orderId. Ensure your WooCommerce bridge sets merchantRef to something like WC{orderId} so you can map it back.
Asynchronous notifications: Always return HTTP 200 quickly to SISP. Do not perform long database or network operations inside the request handler. Use asynchronous functions or ctx.waitUntil() to notify WooCommerce.
7. Testing the Transaction Status API

If you need to query the status of a transaction (for example, when the callback was lost), follow these steps.

Construct the request: Use Basic authentication with your PORTAL_ID and PORTAL_PASSWORD. Build a JSON or form body with posID, posAuthCode and merchantRef. Example using curl:

curl -X POST https://sisp.test.vinti4.cv/transaction-status \
  -u "$PORTAL_ID:$PORTAL_PASSWORD" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"posID":"20314869","posAuthCode":"ttqRdOzmGvCSpuag","merchantRef":"R20240510153000"}'
Interpret the response: A successful transaction returns a status like "success" along with clearingPeriod and transactionID. If you previously marked the session as failed, update it to success. If the status is pending, keep monitoring or mark it as pending. For not found or error statuses, log the result and raise an alert.
Error handling: If the API returns a 401 or 403 error, check your PORTAL_ID and PORTAL_PASSWORD. If you receive a network error, verify the endpoint URL and your network connectivity.
8. Testing tokenization (phase 2)

Tokenization involves three operations: token creation (transactionCode=5), token payments (transactionCode=6) and token cancellation (transactionCode=7). These require additional fields and response handling. For early testing:

Token creation: Send a /create-payment request with transactionCode: "5" and the same purchaseRequest. The callback will include a token field. Verify that you store this token securely in D1 along with its expiry date.
Token payment: Send a new /create-payment request with transactionCode: "6", include the previously received token, and compute the fingerprint accordingly. Validate that SISP charges the card and that the callback indicates success.
Token cancellation: Send a request with transactionCode: "7" and the token. Ensure that the token is removed from your database and that subsequent attempts to use it fail.

Tokenization tests usually involve contacting SISP’s support for test tokens and specific payment scenarios. Refer to the tokenization specification (MOP023) for exact field requirements and expected responses.

9. Logging and Debugging

During all tests, logging is your best friend. Follow these guidelines:

Verbose logs: Include the raw request body, computed fingerprints, expected and received values, and any decisions made by the Worker.
Persistent storage: Store logs in a file or database, not just console output, so that you can review past transactions.
Sensitive data: Do not log full card numbers; mask PAN as in the callback (e.g., ************1234). Avoid logging posAuthCode or portal passwords.
Troubleshooting: If something fails:
Compare the raw request and response payloads to the specification.
Recompute the fingerprint manually with a script to see if your Worker is wrong.
Check the Worker’s environment variables and ensure there are no typos.
For network errors, verify endpoints and firewall settings.
10. Summary

By following this step‑by‑step guide, you will be able to:

Set up the development environment for the Vinti4 Worker.
Run unit tests to validate cryptographic functions and fingerprint logic.
Simulate payment requests and responses locally using Postman or curl.
Handle SISP callbacks correctly, including success and error cases.
Test the transaction status API and lay the groundwork for tokenization.
Log and diagnose any problems that arise during testing.

Once all tests pass locally, you can confidently deploy the Worker to Cloudflare and repeat the tests in the SISP sandbox. Keep your credentials and environment variables separate for development, staging and production to avoid accidental use of real credentials in test environments.
